	<section id="presentation_audio" expanded="true">
		<audio id="narration01">
			<file play="true" bytes="103627" startpos="1" duration="302">a_05_01_01_010_01.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">According to research, the most effective praise is focused on efforts rather than outcomes. Praise helps children understand that their efforts are appreciated, not just their accomplishments. After reviewing more than 20 years of research, Jennifer Henderlong and Mark Lepper concluded that when praise is used in response to a child's effort and accomplishments, it helps the child build confidence. </transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration02">
			<file play="false" bytes="30467" startpos="1" duration="90">a_05_01_01_010_02.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Praise in this context is not conditional affection, but rather affirmation to the children of their genuine strengths.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYHEAD_CHANGE" pos="1" result="SHOW" target="ref_icon01" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration03">
			<file play="false" bytes="87035" startpos="1" duration="254">a_05_01_01_010_03.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">It is important for parents to help children understand that a parents' love and overall acceptance of their child is not dependent on the child's accomplishments or behavior. Praise helps children develop confidence and creates a feeling of being loved and appreciated. Praise is a helpful way for parents to guide children toward positive, appropriate behaviors. </transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYHEAD_CHANGE" pos="1" result="SHOW" target="ref_icon01" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration04">
			<file play="false" bytes="33915" startpos="1" duration="100">a_05_01_01_010_04.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">This is based on the theory that both children and adults will repeat behaviors that feel good but will not repeat those that are unrewarding.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYHEAD_CHANGE" pos="1" result="SHOW" target="ref_icon02" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
		<audio id="narration05">
			<file play="false" bytes="37571" startpos="1" duration="110">a_05_01_01_010_05.swf</file>
			<transcript translate="true">Let's now take a look at the Key Message for this section. It is that: Praise is a way of guiding children toward positive, appropriate behavior.</transcript>
			<notes id="mentor-character">Narrator:</notes>
			<eventlist>
				<event type="PLAYBACK_COMPLETE" result="CONTENT_COMPLETE" target="" result_param=""/>
			</eventlist>
		</audio>
